Predicting Used Car Prices¶

Charles Lu

Introduction¶

To many Americans, car ownership is a symbol of both independence and freedom, but many don't know where to start when it comes to buying their first car. Common wisdom recommends traversing the used car market, but navigating it is confusing and dangerous. There are a number of factors to consider in evaluating the value of a car, including the make, year, condition, and mileage, among others. As a beginner with minimal car experience, it is easy to accidentally overpay for a vehicle. The goal of this tutorial is to help users navigate the 195.84 billion dollar industry by helping users value different used cars, while also learning about the data science pipeline.

Data Collection¶

The first step in the data science pipeline is data collection. This includes both finding data as well as parsing it to prepare it for the rest of the steps in the data science process. For this project, we will use a dataset that is scraped from craigslist, which you can download with a Kaggle account from here. Move the csv file into the same folder as this notebook, and you should be set. Before we get started, we need to import python libraries that we will use. The different libraries that we will use are

  1. Matplotlib
  2. Numpy
  3. Pandas
  4. Seaborn

As we can see above, the data comes with a lot of information that won't be relevant for our purposes, so we will use the drop function to drop irrelevant information such as the description, id, url of images, etc. There are also entries that are incomplete, without information for important features such as price, year, and mileage (odometer). We will use the dropna function from pandas to drop any entries in our dataframe that don't contain information on these important features. It is important to note that this could introduce bias into our dataset, but we will operate under the assumption that the data is missing completely at random for simplicity purposes.

In [ ]:

df.drop(columns=['id', 'url', 'region_url' , 'VIN', 'image_url', 'description', 'lat', 'long', 'posting_date', 'county', 'size', 'type', 'drive', 'title_status', 'cylinders', 'region'], inplace=True)

# remove cars without data on price, year, manufacturer, model, condition, odometer (mileage)
df.dropna(subset=['price', 'year', 'manufacturer', 'model', 'condition', 'odometer'], inplace=True)

Much better. Our data is almost ready. There is still one problem, though. The model column of our dataframe is labeled consistently. As we can see above, some models of car are very similar, but have different names. For example, our dataframe considers a silverado 1500 to be different from a silverado 1500 crew. For the purposes of our model, we will group these together to be the same car. We will do so by making a new column in our dataframe that takes the first word in the manufacturer column and combines it with the first word of the model. A manufacturer gmc model sierra 1500 crew cab slt would simply be a gmc sierra. Lets call this column "car." Also, we have many different car manufacturers in our dataset. Out of tens of thousands of datapoints, there are only 19 Ferraris. Lets focus on the 12 most common manufacturers for simplicity. We also filtered out used cars selling for over $100k USD, since those are extreme outliers. We are now ready for the next step in the data science pipeline.

In [ ]:

# we are only interested with used cars under 100k

Data Exploration¶

Now that we have finished collecting our data, we are ready for the next step, which is data exploration. Lets create some graphs to visualize our daata and get a better feel for what we are working with. The first graph we will create is a simple graph showing the prices of the cars we are working with.

In [ ]:
figure(figsize=(12, 8), dpi=80)
sns.histplot(df['price'])
plt.xlabel('Price')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Prices of Used Cars')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

As we can see, most used cars cost around $0 - $20,000, but there are still a significant amount of cars in the $20,000 - $40,000 price range. For our next plot, we will create a violin plot. Violin plots are great for depicting distributions between multiple groups, since the width of each "violin" is its frequency. Below is a violin plot showing the price of cars based on manufacturer. The gray bar in the middle shows the cost of an average car for each manufacturer. As expected, hondas are the cheapest, but interestingly brands such as GMC and Ram are most expensive.

Machine Learning¶

Now that we have an idea of how different factors affect the price of used vehicles, the next step is to create a model that predicts the price of a car given different factors. For our model, we will use random forest regression, which uses decision trees and ensemble learning. We will use the sklearn python library to do this.

In [ ]:
df.head(5)
Out[ ]:

31 15000 2013 ford f-150 xlt excellent gas 128000.0 automatic black al ford f-150

Our data needs a little more processing before we can feed it to the model. As we can see above, columns such as manufacturer have string values. For this to be usable in the model, they have to be converted to integers. For example, we could map gmc -> 0, chevorlet -> 1, toyota -> 2, and so on. We will use the LabelEncoder function to do this for us.

In [ ]:
# preparing the data for machine learning
from sklearn import preprocessing
label_encoder = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
df['condition']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['condition'])
df['transmission']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['transmission'])
df['paint_color']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['paint_color'])
df['state']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['state'])
df['manufacturer']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['manufacturer'])
df['model']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['model'])
df['fuel']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['fuel'])
df.head(5)

In [ ]:
x = df.loc[:, ['year', 'condition', 'fuel', 'odometer', 'transmission', 'paint_color', 'state', 'manufacturer', 'model']]
y = df.loc[:, ['price']]

We will now store these values in x and y. The one point in x represents all the factors that make up one point in the price y. We will then split this data into a training set and a verification set using the train_test_split function. We will then fit the model using our training data using RandomForestRegressor. As we can see, we have a pretty decent accuracy in predicting prices on our testing set.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 25)

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
rf_reg = RandomForestRegressor()
rf_reg.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_pred= rf_reg.predict(x_test)
print("Accuracy on Training set: ",rf_reg.score(x_train,y_train))
print("Accuracy on Testing set: ",rf_reg.score(x_test,y_test))

Our above model runs with the manufacturer and model as sepereate features. This runs into the problem we described earlier, where many similar models have slightly different model names, based on the user naming it differently on craigslist. This thins out our dataset, and could be the cause of a lower accuracy. Lets try using the column we created called 'car' instead.

In [ ]:
# maybe we can increase accuracy by running each car individually
df['car']= label_encoder.fit_transform(df['car'])
x = df.loc[:, ['year', 'condition', 'fuel', 'odometer', 'transmission', 'paint_color', 'state', 'car']]
y = df.loc[:, ['price']]


x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 25)

rf_reg = RandomForestRegressor()

y_pred= rf_reg.predict(x_test)

Final Insights¶

The final step of the data science process is drawing conclusions and make decisions based on the previous steps. I hope that by following through this tutorial, you have gained a better understanding of the data science process. Additionally, we have been able to create a model that will be able to give the user an idea of the price of a certain used car, based on a number of factors. The next time you are looking at used cars on craigslist, for example, you could be able to get an idea of how much a car should be worth by plugging in the factors into our model. With this tool, hopefully you can be able to make a more informed decision on which used car you want to buy. Thank you for joining me in going through the data science lifecycle!
